14
00:00:57.062 --> 00:01:00.025
2.0 What Is Reaching the Shore

15
00:01:00.025 --> 00:01:09.325
2.0.1 Reaching the shore means living in most civilized regions without needing to pursue unknown cash flow, also known as contemporary financial freedom

16
00:01:09.325 --> 00:01:17.600
2.0.1.1 It is generally believed that RMB 300m in the 2020s achieves contemporary financial freedom

17
00:01:17.600 --> 00:01:25.900
a，RMB 300m/USD 40m is hereinafter WP, p for present, same as Appendix The Track of Chapter 0

18
00:01:25.900 --> 00:01:33.537
b，For brevity, hereinafter no distinction is made between WP and its holder, nor between WP and reaching the shore

19
00:01:33.537 --> 00:01:42.362
2.0.1.2 Hurun estimates approximately 50,000 Chinese households at WP, from low x per mille to low x percent

20
00:01:42.362 --> 00:01:53.575
a，Intuitively: a good ocean-view apartment with four bedrooms and four bathrooms in a prime HK location (April 2025) costs roughly RMB 100m, consuming one-third

21
00:01:53.575 --> 00:02:02.725
b，Generally speaking, RMB 1b is the limit of personally linearly expected usable wealth — beyond that, marginal utility becomes negative

22
00:02:02.725 --> 00:02:09.925
2.0.2 Neither oneself nor one's descendants need pursue unknown cash flow — this is perpetual financial freedom

23
00:02:09.925 --> 00:02:17.537
2.0.2.1 This achievement has academic significance and objectively exists, rather than being accidental

24
00:02:17.537 --> 00:02:25.525
2.0.2.2 It is generally believed that USD 1b in the 2020s can achieve perpetual financial freedom

25
00:02:25.525 --> 00:02:31.800
2.0.2.3 USD 1b is hereinafter WH, h for hurdle.

26
00:02:31.800 --> 00:02:37.100
For brevity, hereinafter no distinction is made between WH and its holder

27
00:02:37.100 --> 00:02:49.062
2.0.2.4 By the natural succession implied by WH's definition, hereinafter no distinction is made between WH and its descendants — all are subject to the constraints on WH

28
00:02:49.062 --> 00:02:56.375
2.0.2.5 When necessary, WH and The Elite from Chapter 0 are collectively referred to as M

29
00:02:56.375 --> 00:03:01.737
We first discuss WP; for perpetual financial freedom see Chapter 3.

30
00:03:01.737 --> 00:03:06.362
It should be noted that WP does not require being among The Elite.

31
00:03:06.362 --> 00:03:09.475
2.1 The Method of Reaching the Shore

32
00:03:09.475 --> 00:03:24.650
2.1.1 The shore-reaching method refers to, for the non-elite, how to achieve 10x+ returns with maximum certainty in a single transaction or medium-term period (5–10 years, hereinafter the same), where the 10x figure is not subject to fluctuation

33
00:03:24.650 --> 00:03:32.387
a，If you have already graduated from Chapter 1, applying the shore-reaching method will achieve W1到WP in the medium term

34
00:03:32.387 --> 00:03:40.712
b，The annualized return of the shore-reaching method is hereinafter Xi; empirically, Xi ∈ (35%, 50%)

35
00:03:40.712 --> 00:03:50.587
2.1.1.1 Like weather forecasting, the shore-reaching method is a counter-conventional / beyond-normal-rules technique — it cannot offer 100% certainty

36
00:03:50.587 --> 00:03:56.037
2.1.1.2 Like weather forecasting, the shore-reaching method is a science.

37
00:03:56.037 --> 00:04:00.387
When preconditions are precisely met, wins outnumber losses

38
00:04:00.387 --> 00:04:05.750
The author has witnessed many people apply the shore-reaching method to achieve WP

39
00:04:05.750 --> 00:04:11.400
2.1.2 This work defaults to using listed Chinese company stocks as examples

40
00:04:11.400 --> 00:04:21.400
2.1.2.1 Reaching the shore is extraordinary (x per mille); in practice it is difficult to achieve purely through stock investing (the stakes involved are too small)

41
00:04:21.400 --> 00:04:27.537
2.1.2.2 Reaching the shore through other investment vehicles follows similar principles

42
00:04:27.537 --> 00:04:31.737
2.1.3 Why can Xi significantly exceed Rm?

43
00:04:31.737 --> 00:04:34.975
Three core constraints breaking through Rm

44
00:04:34.975 --> 00:04:42.275
2.1.3.0 Only WH can enjoy long-term perpetual returns (see Chapter 3 for details).

45
00:04:42.275 --> 00:04:45.700
Such returns are constrained by three factors:

46
00:04:45.700 --> 00:04:50.175
2.1.3.1 Constraint One: Market Opportunity

47
00:04:50.332 --> 00:04:56.232
a，"Off-market deals" that can only absorb small amounts of capital are meaningless to WH

48
00:04:56.182 --> 00:05:08.419
Taking A-shares as an example: a stock with market cap RMB 10b trades roughly RMB 150m daily; active buying of just RMB 15m in a day is enough to trigger the daily limit-up

49
00:05:08.419 --> 00:05:16.157
Active position-building of USD 150m may double your average entry cost (7 consecutive limit-ups).

50
00:05:16.157 --> 00:05:18.569
The same applies when selling

51
00:05:18.569 --> 00:05:28.157
Investing USD 150m and earning USD 150m back is only possible with large-cap stocks like Moutai or Yangtze Power

52
00:05:28.157 --> 00:05:35.582
b，If the initial capital required to reach the shore is small enough to pursue off-market opportunities, then it may exceed Rm

53
00:05:35.582 --> 00:05:40.057
2.1.3.2 Constraint Two: Long-Term Compounding

54
00:05:40.057 --> 00:05:46.857
a，The best investments in the world, such as Monet's Water Lilies, have GRm as their perpetual growth ceiling

55
00:05:46.857 --> 00:05:56.019
b，Reaching the shore requires only one success: capturing the reversal phase from crash to stabilization or even to major rally, which may exceed GRm

56
00:05:56.019 --> 00:06:00.819
2.1.3.3 Constraint Three: Extremely High Certainty

57
00:06:00.819 --> 00:06:08.332
a，What WH essentially does is near risk-free trading — they neither need nor should chase returns from value system restructuring

58
00:06:08.332 --> 00:06:15.982
b，Reaching the shore demands a strong gambling spirit: participating in the establishment of new value systems may exceed Rm

59
00:06:15.982 --> 00:06:20.882
2.1.4 Three types of shore-reaching methods arise from the above

60
00:06:20.882 --> 00:06:29.632
2.1.4.1 First type breaks Constraint 2.1.3.1, denoted X1: IRR 50%, MOC 5-year 8x

61
00:06:29.632 --> 00:06:38.807
2.1.4.2 Second type breaks Constraint 2.1.3.2, denoted X2: IRR 40%, MOC 7-year 12x

62
00:06:38.807 --> 00:06:47.982
2.1.4.3 Third type breaks Constraint 2.1.3.3, denoted X3: IRR 35%, MOC 10-year 18x

63
00:06:47.982 --> 00:06:52.982
2.1.4.4 Some notes on the median returns of the above Xi

64
00:06:52.982 --> 00:07:00.732
a，IRR stands for internal rate of return, i.e., expected investment return; MOC is the return multiple mentioned earlier

65
00:07:00.732 --> 00:07:11.044
b，IRR and time horizons have standard deviations; MOC values represent single-use medians, independent of principal, non-compoundable, with standard deviations

66
00:07:11.044 --> 00:07:14.119
2.2 The First Shore-Reaching Method

67
00:07:14.119 --> 00:07:25.794
2.2.0 The first principle of X1 is: high-return certainty comes from the scarcity of the trading opportunity (i.e., good price), not from certainty about the asset itself (i.e., good company)

68
00:07:25.794 --> 00:07:32.607
Such high-certainty, high-return transactions accessible only to a minority are hereinafter called X1 deals

69
00:07:32.607 --> 00:07:42.394
2.2.0.1 Common examples include spin-offs of new-track subsidiaries by corporate giants, and the final financing round before industry leaders go public

70
00:07:42.394 --> 00:07:46.269
None of the above are secondary market transactions.

71
00:07:46.269 --> 00:07:53.494
Early-stage private equity investment is called VC; mid-to-late stage through pre-IPO is called PE — hereinafter the same

72
00:07:53.494 --> 00:08:02.969
2.2.0.2 The underlying assets of an X1 deal do not possess the certainty of The Portfolio, but their transaction prices are extremely attractive

73
00:08:02.969 --> 00:08:08.832
2.2.0.3 This work defaults to using listed Chinese company stock examples

74
00:08:08.832 --> 00:08:17.432
a，Stock investment naturally does not restrict participation by number of people — rather, it restricts those who understand and dare to participate.

75
00:08:17.432 --> 00:08:24.882
That is, X1 deals arise from fundamental positive changes in a listed company that only a minority can deeply comprehend

76
00:08:24.882 --> 00:08:29.507
b，For certain reasons, only a hypothetical example is given

77
00:08:29.507 --> 00:08:37.432
Assume publicly available information shows a private aerospace company secured an order from Shanghai Yuanxin Satellite Technology

78
00:08:37.432 --> 00:08:44.144
But not everyone understands what this implies before China's version of Starlink is built in April 2025

79
00:08:44.144 --> 00:08:52.619
2.2.1 The first shore-reaching method refers to the technique of securing a place in an X1 deal by leveraging one's own commercial influence

80
00:08:52.619 --> 00:09:05.369
2.2.1.1 Essentially, investing (paying cash together with a group of people to purchase equity, same shares same rights) is merely the necessary form and optimal vehicle for monetizing personal commercial influence

81
00:09:05.369 --> 00:09:12.282
2.2.1.2 Other methods of monetizing commercial influence are not recommended (examples omitted)

82
00:09:12.282 --> 00:09:15.894
2.2.2 Why do X1 deals exist?

83
00:09:15.894 --> 00:09:24.669
2.2.2.1 Trading is a short-term activity during which market vacuums may exist (only one buyer/seller within a certain period)

84
00:09:24.820 --> 00:09:34.870
2.2.2.2 If the asset is sufficiently good, trading during a market vacuum period is actually zero-risk — the sole buyer/seller enjoys full pricing power

85
00:09:34.820 --> 00:09:38.832
2.2.2.3 Take Buffett as an example.

86
00:09:38.832 --> 00:09:52.107
In reality, he possesses no extraordinary mathematical intelligence or risk-pricing ability; Berkshire Hathaway is essentially an acquisition company where he chooses his battlefield and conducts simple, rough, fault-tolerant risk pricing

87
00:09:52.276 --> 00:09:54.151
a，Specifically:

88
00:09:54.101 --> 00:10:00.138
Only do risk-free trades that only he can execute; exit at satisfactory IRR passively

89
00:10:00.138 --> 00:10:03.288
Any mega-PE firm could meet this bar

90
00:10:03.288 --> 00:10:06.251
Only do sufficiently large trades

91
00:10:06.251 --> 00:10:15.126
During the 2008 financial crisis, Buffett invested in Goldman Sachs: crisis pricing + preferred stock + high dividends + warrants

92
00:10:15.126 --> 00:10:21.051
This was clearly asymmetric deal terms, but during the financial crisis he was the sole bidder

93
00:10:21.051 --> 00:10:26.351
2.2.3 Core elements and empirical characteristics of X1 deals

94
00:10:26.351 --> 00:10:33.251
2.2.3.1 The asset must be good — at the level of a top-tier industry leader, hereinafter "top-tier

95
00:10:33.251 --> 00:10:39.638
a，While it lacks long-term certainty, it has short-to-medium term certainty at a specific time and place

96
00:10:39.638 --> 00:10:46.663
b，Below the "top-tier" level, any action taken on such assets yields long-term negative-sum outcomes in terms of interest

97
00:10:46.663 --> 00:10:50.226
Its own growth is insufficient to pay off everyone

98
00:10:50.226 --> 00:10:54.163
That is, not everyone who participates will fare well.

99
00:10:54.163 --> 00:10:57.676
This is inevitably high-risk — the wise avoid it

100
00:10:57.676 --> 00:11:02.051
2.2.3.2 This trading opportunity is scarce

101
00:11:02.051 --> 00:11:08.526
a，Scarcity generally means not merely the ability to buy at a discount, but that others cannot buy at all

102
00:11:08.526 --> 00:11:14.051
b，Or others can buy but, due to information asymmetry, dare not buy at the same price

103
00:11:14.051 --> 00:11:18.938
2.2.3.3 Empirical characteristics of X1 deals

104
00:11:18.938 --> 00:11:24.738
a，85%+ probability of achieving a deterministic 5–10x return

105
00:11:24.738 --> 00:11:32.826
One successful capture before retirement suffices; beforehand, slowly accumulate commercial influence / wait for opportunity

106
00:11:32.826 --> 00:11:38.763
b，You must be a necessary link in this transaction — you cannot buy someone else's story/rumor

107
00:11:38.763 --> 00:11:44.851
You wouldn't dare buy much of another person's rumor; net profit insufficient makes it not worth risking

108
00:11:44.851 --> 00:11:51.513
If you're not on the front line of the transaction, once conditions deteriorate, you won't understand the dynamics

109
00:11:51.513 --> 00:11:57.263
c，Commitment should be no less than e-1 of personal net worth, median 100%

110
00:11:57.263 --> 00:12:00.813
d，Bet to the end — "fight until complete victory

111
00:12:00.813 --> 00:12:05.751
2.2.4 Non-elite individuals may possess commercial influence

112
00:12:05.751 --> 00:12:11.763
2.2.4.1 The Elite are those willing to Serve Original Dishes to the world — and they need help

113
00:12:11.763 --> 00:12:19.526
2.2.4.2 Logically, "you served this dish" and "without you, this dish couldn't have been served" are different propositions

114
00:12:19.526 --> 00:12:25.451
2.2.4.3 The difference between the latter and the former is called commercial influence

115
00:12:25.451 --> 00:12:40.926
a，Taking an M&A transaction as example: typical persons with commercial include target company shareholders and management; headquarters of major commercial banks, M&A lending departments, handling branches; acquirer's boss and core employees; regulatory authorities

116
00:12:40.926 --> 00:12:44.238
b，And key assistants to all of the above

117
00:12:44.238 --> 00:12:49.526
2.2.4. I almost never have influence in any transaction — what then?

118
00:12:49.526 --> 00:12:53.276
Then you're suited for the second or third shore-reaching method

119
00:12:53.276 --> 00:12:59.726
2.2.5 Core elements of the transaction structure / realization method for X1 deals

120
00:12:59.726 --> 00:13:04.663
2.2.5.1 Must be indisputably legal and compliant

121
00:13:04.663 --> 00:13:12.001
a，Laws/regulations/rules are not immutable — it must remain legal and compliant under generous interpretation

122
00:13:12.001 --> 00:13:19.913
b，For example, involving listed companies: if there's no particularly valid reason to buy before a trading halt, buy after resumption

123
00:13:19.913 --> 00:13:29.413
c，For X1 deals, window returns arising from halts/resumptions (return differential between buying before vs. after halt) are entirely irrelevant

124
00:13:29.413 --> 00:13:36.851
2.2.5.2 The more you share the same profit mechanism with commercially influential persons, the safer it is

125
00:13:36.851 --> 00:13:39.063
Safety in numbers

126
00:13:39.063 --> 00:13:51.588
2.2.5.3 If sharing profit mechanisms with many isn't possible, align as closely as possible with a very wealthy individual/institution's profit mechanism — this is the next-safest realization method

127
00:13:51.588 --> 00:13:55.651
a，The standard is: what you take should be negligible to them

128
00:13:55.651 --> 00:14:02.951
2.2.5.4 If all laws of capitalism were summarized in one sentence: always stand on the side of the rich.

129
00:14:02.951 --> 00:14:10.388
For the non-elite, aligning profit mechanisms with the rich is self-protection — because the rich have far less motive to default on you

130
00:14:10.388 --> 00:14:13.963
2.2.6 Three examples of X1

131
00:14:13.963 --> 00:14:18.663
2.2.6.1 A formerly worked at a foreign PE firm

132
00:14:18.820 --> 00:14:21.857
a，Resigned during a project spin-off.

133
00:14:21.807 --> 00:14:26.395
Personally invested in the new company's formation and became vice-chairman

134
00:14:26.395 --> 00:14:30.795
b，Currently considered the wealthiest among ex-PE practitioners

135
00:14:30.795 --> 00:14:35.682
2.2.6.2 B formerly worked at a domestic PE firm

136
00:14:35.682 --> 00:14:39.757
a，The firm's investment committee rejected a certain project.

137
00:14:39.757 --> 00:14:44.970
He mortgaged his house and invested nearly 100% of his personal net worth

138
00:14:44.970 --> 00:14:51.745
b，The project later accumulated low double-digit returns, with net profit in the RMB 1b range

139
00:14:51.745 --> 00:14:56.182
2.2.6.3 C, owner of a foreign PE firm

140
00:14:56.332 --> 00:15:02.182
a，Personally invested in the first large-scale Chinese concept stock privatization transaction.

141
00:15:02.132 --> 00:15:07.982
Because the market had no precedent, privatization proceeded smoothly at reasonable cost

142
00:15:07.982 --> 00:15:13.919
b，Secured high single-digit returns smoothly, net profit in the RMB 1b range

143
00:15:13.919 --> 00:15:17.144
2.3 The Second Shore-Reaching Method

144
00:15:17.144 --> 00:15:26.157
2.3.0 The first principle of X2 is: high-return certainty comes from severe prior decline AND reversal certainty — both are indispensable

145
00:15:26.157 --> 00:15:33.232
Such high-return transactions featuring prior crash + deterministic reversal are hereinafter called X2 deals

146
00:15:33.232 --> 00:15:41.007
2.3.1 The second shore-reaching method refers to the technique of reaching the shore through reversal investing / X2 deals

147
00:15:41.007 --> 00:15:47.232
For the main academic viewpoints and practices of reversal investing, see the appendix to this chapter

148
00:15:47.232 --> 00:15:57.044
2.3.1.1 In the turnaround of an X2 deal, there must be a key person/party playing a central rescue role (typically a new CEO / new shareholder)

149
00:15:57.044 --> 00:16:00.244
Hereinafter White Knight / WK

150
00:16:00.244 --> 00:16:06.682
2.3.1.2 The certainty of an X2 deal derives from WK's rescue capability

151
00:16:06.682 --> 00:16:15.282
It should be noted that WK also brings massive positive changes to the target company that only a minority can understand — but differs from X1

152
00:16:15.282 --> 00:16:21.669
a，X1 deal excess returns mainly come from trading scarcity — monetization of commercial influence

153
00:16:21.669 --> 00:16:29.107
b，X2 deal excess returns mainly come from severe prior decline and WK ultimately avoiding its extinction risk

154
00:16:29.107 --> 00:16:39.557
2.3.1.3 Therefore, completing an X2 deal does not require commercial influence — but it requires you to have above-market understanding of and confidence in WK

155
00:16:39.557 --> 00:16:43.032
a，You need to determine only: "Who will rescue?

156
00:16:43.032 --> 00:16:45.544
Is the rescuer reliable?

157
00:16:45.544 --> 00:16:47.257
That's enough

158
00:16:47.257 --> 00:16:58.832
b，In any endeavor, even win-win ones, among resource-holding, influential parties, at least one person must be responsible/decent/professional — commonly known as having "someone to backstop.

159
00:16:58.832 --> 00:17:01.919
Bad actors cannot accomplish good things.

160
00:17:01.919 --> 00:17:04.694
The backstop must be reliable.

161
00:17:04.694 --> 00:17:08.357
2.3.2 Why do X2 deals exist?

162
00:17:08.357 --> 00:17:13.307
2.3.2.0 The investment target must reach top-tier level

163
00:17:13.307 --> 00:17:20.932
2.3.2.1 Severe decline means dropping 90% from the prior peak, then declining further by roughly e-1

164
00:17:20.932 --> 00:17:28.132
a，The first 90% is certain; the subsequent e-1 has a range of ±e-1 (in growth ratio terms)

165
00:17:28.132 --> 00:17:31.244
b，A 90% drop isn't enough.

166
00:17:31.244 --> 00:17:38.157
Empirically, if something has dropped 90%, it usually falls further (see appendix on "Reflexivity")

167
00:17:38.157 --> 00:17:45.594
2.3.2.2 Dropping 90% means the market believes this formerly top-tier asset faces extinction risk

168
00:17:45.594 --> 00:17:54.744
2.3.2.3 There are two causes: either the environment underwent fundamental change, or the company committed serious operational misconduct

169
00:17:54.744 --> 00:17:59.107
Colloquially: "shot themselves in the foot" (made a fatal blunder)

170
00:17:59.107 --> 00:18:03.607
2.3.2.4 Only the second cause is salvageable.

171
00:18:03.607 --> 00:18:06.694
The first is mostly unsalvageable

172
00:18:06.694 --> 00:18:13.444
a，A 90% drop means the market believes this company no longer serves any purpose under the new environment

173
00:18:13.444 --> 00:18:17.644
b，A company typically cannot change its macro environment.

174
00:18:17.644 --> 00:18:23.157
Without self-inflicted damage, every reasonable response would already have been deployed.

175
00:18:23.157 --> 00:18:27.169
Continued decline indicates human effort is exhausted

176
00:18:27.169 --> 00:18:32.894
c，What if the environmental cause later improves (e.g., temporary policy changes)?

177
00:18:32.894 --> 00:18:36.857
Possible, but rational investors cannot bet on this

178
00:18:36.857 --> 00:18:47.244
Policy changes generally have profound, irreversible reasons (e.g., China's "Double Reduction" policy on tutoring, grounded in deep social fairness and demographic foundations)

179
00:18:47.244 --> 00:18:54.082
If the cause were reversible/temporary, the market would be smart enough that the drop rarely reaches 90%

180
00:18:54.082 --> 00:19:02.769
d，When the environment hasn't changed but the company shot itself in the foot, recovery is much easier — simply returning to its former self suffices

181
00:19:02.769 --> 00:19:06.369
If WK is capable, this is achievable

182
00:19:06.369 --> 00:19:17.157
2.3.2.5 Misconduct by original shareholders/management on the liability/distribution side generally doesn't directly affect asset/operations in the long run

183
00:19:17.157 --> 00:19:22.069
a，Assets remain quality assets; brands often remain strong brands

184
00:19:22.069 --> 00:19:29.082
b，For top-tier leaders, if you think they've made a recoverable blunder, other capable institutions surely think so too

185
00:19:29.236 --> 00:19:37.311
c，Eventually, a capable WK will emerge who judges the target worth saving, believes they can revive it, and dives in personally

186
00:19:37.261 --> 00:19:42.611
2.3.3 Core elements and empirical characteristics of X2 deals

187
00:19:42.611 --> 00:19:49.861
2.3.3.1 WK's strength, credibility, and experience must exceed those of the rescued company

188
00:19:49.861 --> 00:19:58.286
Typically elite entrepreneurs/acquisition funds become new owners; or with dispersed ownership, capable management becomes new CEO

189
00:19:58.286 --> 00:20:06.123
This must not be WK's first/only project — their rescue capability remains unvalidated, and win rate is insufficient

190
00:20:06.292 --> 00:20:11.329
2.3.3.2 WK must have skin in the game — fully committed

191
00:20:11.279 --> 00:20:16.529
If they don't rescue, they suffer personal loss — not merely opportunistic trial

192
00:20:16.529 --> 00:20:23.879
