2.8.2.2 Investment style: acts once per decade, frequently at RMB tens-of-billions scale, purchasing only strategically important best-in-class assets

385
00:40:12.782 --> 00:40:19.520
a，Philosophically, unique quality assets are always cheapest long-term — "fear of heights is the lot of the unfortunate

386
00:40:19.520 --> 00:40:23.645
2.8.2.3 Its Chinese investments include:

387
00:40:23.645 --> 00:40:27.820
a，China X Group / J Company mixed-ownership reform

388
00:40:27.820 --> 00:40:32.170
b，Two Grade-A office towers in Beijing CBD core area

389
00:40:32.170 --> 00:40:36.295
c，ZG Biotech (shareholder of KX vaccine)

390
00:40:36.295 --> 00:40:42.270
2.8.3 Practical Reversal Investing Example 2: Hong Kong Property Stocks

391
00:40:42.436 --> 00:40:49.773
2.8.3.1 HK's priciest property viewings often require proof of assets in tens or hundreds of millions

392
00:40:49.723 --> 00:40:58.386
2.8.3.2 Yet the finest HK property stocks, like Sun Hung Kai, over a 20-year horizon always reach PE 5x at some point

393
00:40:58.386 --> 00:41:05.048
2.8.4 Practical Reversal Investing Example 3: Diversified Reversal-Factor Investing

394
00:41:05.048 --> 00:41:17.736
2.8.4.1 Ordinary people lack access to exclusively buy the highest-certainty assets (as in the two examples above), but the phenomenon that ordinary assets (short-term) refuse to fall further may exist

395
00:41:17.884 --> 00:41:24.446
a，Facing life-threatening danger (e.g., at gunpoint), few immediately flee — most freeze in fear and numbness

396
00:41:24.396 --> 00:41:32.384
b，Similarly, an asset experiencing multiple rounds of sharp decline and prolonged bottom oscillation enters a so-called oversold state

397
00:41:32.384 --> 00:41:41.134
c，Among oversold-state assets, removing portions with fast-extinction risk and investing in a diversified way often achieves ~30% returns

398
00:41:41.134 --> 00:41:49.034
2.8.5 This merits mention because it is arguably the only academic strategy exceeding GRm=20%

399
00:41:49.034 --> 00:41:53.784
2.8.6 Reversal investing is not suitable for everyone

400
00:41:53.784 --> 00:41:58.859
2.8.6.1 Investment style mirrors investor personality

401
00:41:58.859 --> 00:42:04.421
Those who love oversold bargains generally dislike buying quality assets, and vice versa

402
00:42:04.421 --> 00:42:11.896
2.8.6.2 This technique is currently fully armed — nearly only institutional professional operations are viable

403
00:42:11.896 --> 00:42:17.309
2.8.6.3 Poor application leads to value traps and severe losses

404
00:42:17.309 --> 00:42:21.709
a，A company valued below its book free cash is quite ordinary

405
00:42:21.709 --> 00:42:25.684
b，Two examples of "market cap below cash on books":

406
00:42:25.684 --> 00:42:33.359
An HK-listed company held RMB 500m cash on books, but market cap was only RMB 400m

407
00:42:33.359 --> 00:42:38.621
Natural thought: buy it, dissolve it, and it's worth RMB 500m?

408
00:42:38.621 --> 00:42:44.209
But it won't dissolve — management expenses travel and entertainment on the company dime daily

409
00:42:44.209 --> 00:42:49.684
Management is so terrible no WK is willing to step forward for privatization

410
00:42:49.684 --> 00:42:53.259
Capital C raised an Ethereum metaverse fund

411
00:42:53.259 --> 00:42:59.571
Operation: convert raised USD to ETH, then invest ETH into metaverse projects

412
00:42:59.571 --> 00:43:06.584
Fund ultimately liquidated: earned 2–3x in USD terms but lost 90%+ in ETH terms

413
00:43:06.584 --> 00:43:13.959
I.e., if they'd simply held ETH post-fundraising without investing in any projects, they'd have earned 10x–20x

414
00:43:13.959 --> 00:43:19.859
c，Oversold ordinary assets merely resist falling short-term; long-term extinction is certain

415
00:43:19.859 --> 00:43:26.771
d，Some top-tier companies appear to have dropped significantly and present opportunity, but they are no longer who they were

416
00:43:26.771 --> 00:43:31.584
For understanding this point, see main text 2.3.2.4

417
00:43:31.584 --> 00:43:34.859
Both Elite and Non-Elite versions*

